{
  "analysis": "We are at a fresh terminal as root. No output yet. Need to create directory /srv/shared, set up group research, users alice and bob, set permissions and ACLs. First check if group research and users exist; if not create them. Then create directory, set ownership and permissions, set ACLs with setfacl. Ensure proper inheritance with default ACLs.",
  "plan": "1. Check if group research exists; if not create. 2. Check if users alice and bob exist; if not create them. 3. Create directory /srv/shared. 4. Set group ownership to research. 5. Set permissions 2770. 6. Set ACLs: setfacl -m g:research:rwx,u:alice:rwx,u:bob:rwx /srv/shared. 7. Set default ACLs: setfacl -d -m g:research:rwx,u:alice:rwx,u:bob:rwx /srv/shared. 8. Verify with getfacl. Ensure mask is set to rwx. Also ensure others have no permissions (default ACL for others is none). Might need to explicitly set default for others to none? By default default ACL entries are inherited from the base ACL; we can set default others to none. Let's do that: setfacl -d -m o::--- /srv/shared. Also ensure mask is rwx; setfacl -m m::rwx /srv/shared and setfacl -d -m m::rwx /srv/shared. Let's implement stepwise.",
